%N A387908 a(n) is the number of distinct integer-sided triangles with perimeter 6*n and integer area whose sides are in arithmetic progression.
%C A387908 Integer-sided triangles with perimeter p that is not divisible by 6 cannot have side lengths in arithmetic progression and integer area. Proof: Let the three sides be in arithmetic progression: (x, y, z) = (p/3 - d, p/3, p/3 + d), where p is the perimeter. By Heron's formula, the area A is A = sqrt((p/2)*(p/6 + d)*(p/6)*(p/6 - d)). If p is not divisible by 6, then the radicand is not a perfect square, so A is not an integer. Hence, no integer-sided triangle with sides in arithmetic progression can have integer area when 6 does not divide p.
%C A387908 There is no triangle with integer area for d = 0 because A = sqrt(3*n*n*n*n) = sqrt(3)*n^2.
%C A387908 Right triangles counted in this sequence are of the form (3*k, 4*k, 5*k), where k is a positive integer. In terms with even n >= 2 therefore one right triangle is counted.
%C A387908 Observation: For n <= 50000, a(n) takes the values {0, 1, 2, 4, 7, 13, 22, 37, 40, 67}.
%H A387908 Felix Huber, <a href="/A387908/b387908.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..10000</a>
%H A387908 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ArithmeticProgression.html">Arithmetic Progression</a>
%H A387908 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/HeronianTriangle.html">Heronian Triangle</a>
%F A387908 a(n) <= min(A024164(6*n), A051516(6*n)) for n >= 1.
%F A387908 a(2*k) >= 1 for positive integer k.
%e A387908 The a(14) = 4 distinct integer-sided triangles with perimeter 14*6 = 84 and integer area whose sides are in arithmetic progression are (15, 28, 41) with area 126, (17, 28, 39) with area 210, (21, 28, 35) with area 294 and (26, 28, 30) with area 336.
%p A387908 A387908:=proc(n)
%p A387908     local a,d;
%p A387908     a:=0;
%p A387908     for d to n-1 do
%p A387908         if issqr((n^2-d^2)/3) then
%p A387908             a:=a+1
%p A387908         fi
%p A387908     od;
%p A387908     return a
%p A387908 end proc;
%p A387908 seq(A387908(n),n=0..87);
%t A387908 A387908[n_]:=Module[{a = 0, d},For[d = 0, d <= n - 1, d++,If[IntegerQ[Sqrt[(n^2 - d^2)/3]], a = a + 1]];a];Array[A387908,88,0] (* _James C. McMahon_, Oct 15 2025 *)
